{"title":{"rendered":"Walking Palm (Socratea exorrhiza)"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><a href=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01202627/Bruce_walkingpalm.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-large wp-image-7783\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01202627/Bruce_walkingpalm-758x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"758\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01202627/Bruce_walkingpalm-758x1024.jpg 758w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01202627/Bruce_walkingpalm-222x300.jpg 222w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01202627/Bruce_walkingpalm-768x1037.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01202627/Bruce_walkingpalm.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px\" /></a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">I heard a rumor of a tree that can walk. Its footprints don’t last long, quickly erased by the jungle floor. They say it can right itself if toppled by a fallen neighbor, sprouting shoots from its torso. It moves quickly for a tree, in search of water and stable soil — but too slowly for any of us to notice. The walking palm’s roots are like probes, poking through the soil for a bountiful home. The probes converge on a pedestal, a gimbal for the trunk as it spars the forest.</p>\n"},"meta":{"contributors":[{"title":{"rendered":"Samuel David Bruce"},"slug":"david-bruce","meta":{"degree":"M.Arch I","graduation_year":"2020"}}],"fold":{"title":{"rendered":"Trees for the Forest"},"slug":"trees","meta":{"volume":"5","number":"17","bulletin":false,"publication_date":"2020-04-02"}}}}